Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco — February 24, the Russian invasion of Ukraine marks the beginning of the third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a long meeting on February 4 — the day marking the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two released a carefully drafted 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and certainly requires detailed negotiations in advance.
I was shocked that Xi seemed to fully entrust Putin with invading and waging war in Ukraine.
He believed that confirming himself as the lifelong ruler of China by the second half of this year was merely a formality, and he was certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set about realizing his lifelong dream in an unbelievably brutal manner.
A 69-year-old Putin felt that if he wanted to leave a lasting mark in Russian history, it would either be now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a Tsar to blindly follow.
This system is the opposite of a democratic society, and this vision distorts the emotionally sensitive souls of the Russian people to an extreme.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I began what I called my political charitable work.
At first, I established a foundation in my home country, Hungary, and then I actively participated in activities that led to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this process of dissolution had already begun.
I also set up foundations in Russia, and then in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly after the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have been closely watching his rise and fully understand his cruel and ruthless nature.
He levelled Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to the ground, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality, because he has developed a fixed mindset.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He assumed that the Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but in reality, they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Despite the seemingly one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people carried out an incredibly courageous resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article claiming that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians had been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Since Kyiv was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument was not without historical basis.
But it was Putin who was misled in Part 2.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The 2014 events made him very angry.
But when the Russian military was ordered to attack his Ukrainian brothers, they performed poorly.
The deep-rooted corruption within the Ministry of Defense also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin not only did not blame himself, but seemed to have gone mad.
He has resolved to punish Ukraine, which opposes him, and his actions seem to have no constraints.
He committed the entire Russian army to battle and disregarded all combat rules, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In the besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have had no water or food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine while also trying to purchase Russian-made MIG fighters that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These developments could change the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has created a miracle in strengthening European resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has been unfaithful.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi firmly stated that the friendship between China and Russia remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
In order to avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to maintain maximum restraint during the war.
It is still uncertain whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
